\intbl \ql \b Summary of Evaluator Report\b0 \line The evaluator indicated that all criteria are in need of improvement to meet minimum standards. The evaluator recommends that the programme should not be accredited. As was the case with similar programmes submitted by the institution\'2C much of the concerns relate to the distance education model proposed \'28see Higher Certificate in Community Development\'29. The institution plans to adopt the Multi-media Model which would enhance the interactivity at both individual and social levels\'3B  and access to a range of teaching-learning resources.  Use will be made of the Cyber-classroom\'2C where students are able to use Scalable Video Coding to interrupt the presenter to ask questions or request a detailed explanation of the educational material when necessary.  Contact sessions will be recorded on DVD\'E2\'80\'99s and uploaded onto YouTube where they can be accessed through the Internet\'2C Twitter\'2C Face book\'2C etc.  The evaluator noted that this all seems attractive and accessible to the working class.  No mention is however made of provision that is made for school leavers\'E2\'80\'99 training to use this technology.  This might restrict access.\line \line According to the evaluator proper market analysis has been conducted for the programme. It has been benchmarked against the new Higher Education Qualifications Framework \'28HEQF\'29 and the draft level descriptors of the SAQA and CESM categories - the programme is pitched at NQF level 5 with 120 credits. The articulation possibilities have clearly spelled out and provision is also made for the learners to carry the credits to other programmes - reference is here made to the programme Cognate Advanced Higher Certificate and Diploma.  The evaluator states that inherent in this Diploma \'28sic\'29 is the inclusion of Front Office Duties\'2FActivities in the curriculum content.  This component is however missing in the AK submission. One would expect to find them in subjects such as Administrative Practice and\'2For Office Systems and Procedures.  It is not clear from the evaluator\'27s report whether he\'2Fshe was looking at it as a diploma and not a higher certificate and if this is an essential requirement for a HC in Office Administration. The same applies to the claim that Professional Associations should be invited to give input into the curriculation process. As an entry level qualification this should not be required.  \line The evaluator also pointed out that the programme caters for Experiential Learning opportunities with the associated outcomes spelled out.  The fact that the institution has monitoring procedures in place and is responsible for the placement of students is commendable.  Of concern is that there is no Experiential Learning co-ordinator for this programme.  This person would facilitate liaison with the industry and other stakeholders. \line In terms of Criterion 2 and 6 the evaluator felt that a more rigorous RPL process\'2C geared towards this programme needs to be detailed given the fact that working adults would possess a vast amount of varied work experience which would require the institution to recognize as prior knowledge that they bring into their studies.\line The evaluator stated that staff members have adequate and relevant qualifications \'28one-level higher\'29\'2C but no teaching experience.  Only one staff member has the required teaching experience \'285 years\'29. The majority of the staff members are also employed on a part-time basis. The evaluator also felt that the programme co-ordinator and experiential learning co-ordinator should be persons with extensive knowledge and training in the secretarial\'2Fadministrative field so that they can provide the necessary academic leadership.\line The Directorate does not support the recommendation of the evaluator and recommends that the programme be accredited with conditions.\line \cell \pard 

